Donald Trump

Betting odds and polls: who will be the next US president?

Aug 8, 2018

A second term for Donald Trump has the shortest odds for 2020, but it may depend on his challengers

  • whatsapp
  • facebook
  • twitter
  • google+
  • linkedin
  • email
Chris Kleponis-Pool/Getty Images

The upcoming midterm elections have the potential for a seismic shock in the US, but attention is already turning to the next presidential elections in 2020.

See related 
Midterm elections 2018: why they are so important
Who is Q and what does the pro-Trump conspiracy theory QAnon believe?
Donald Trump says Mueller probe must end ‘right now’

In February of this year Donald Trump confirmed he would run for a second term as president and, according to BBC News, he had already raised $22m (£17m) by the end of 2017 for his campaign to remain in the White House.

Trump’s re-election is the most likely outcome, according to Oddschecker, which aggregates online betting odds from the top bookmakers.

Who could replace Trump?

Discounting a Trump win, victory for the Democrats looks most likely to come from “a small advance guard” led by Senator Elizabeth Warren who “appear to be moving deliberately toward challenging President Trump”, says The New York Times.

In their number, they count former vice president Joe Biden, who “wielding a political network cultivated over decades, has been reasserting himself as a party leader”, adds the paper.

Senators Cory Booker of New Jersey and Kamala Harris of California have also emerged as fresher-faced alternatives.

The Democrat presidential primaries are “almost certainly going to break down along similar lines as the 2016 primary, with a left faction and a centrist faction - only with many more candidates”, says The Week US’s Ryan Cooper.

On the left, Bernie Sanders “is by far the most credible candidate and the probable frontrunner, with a mile-long record of consistent principles. Elizabeth Warren doesn't have quite as good a record, but she is better on details, a bit younger, and a woman”, says Cooper.

As a group, they are “a strikingly heterogeneous array of rivals for Trump, embodying the Democratic Party’s options for defining itself”, notes the Times. They are distinguished by “gender and race, span three decades in age and traverse the ideological and tonal spectrum between combative Democratic socialism and consensus-minded incrementalism”, adds the paper.

In terms of odds, Harris currently holds favour with the bookies, followed by Sanders, Warren, Biden and then a bit further back is Booker.

What about the Republicans?

Republican Senator Jeff Flake was asked earlier this year whether he thinks someone should challenge Trump in the 2020 Republican primary.

“Yes, I do. I do,” Flake told CNN. “I mean, it would be a tough go in a Republican primary. The Republican Party is the Trump party right now. But that's not to say it will stay that way.”

Apart from Flake himself, the bookies have Paul Ryan, John Kasich and - as something of a rogue outsider - Mitt Romney possibly challenging Trump during the primaries.

To highlight the unlikelihood of a Republican president other than Trump in 2020, only once before has a sitting president failed to be nominated for a second term and that was Franklin Pierce way back in 1852.

A Republican challenger may be good news for the Democrats as “most of the time, presidents who fend off a primary challenge wind up losing the general election”, says CBS News.

What are the odds on Trump’s impeachment?

Other than Trump, the best-placed Republican on all the bookies’ lists remains Mike Pence, at sixth favourite.

Trump’s vice-president is steadfastly loyal to his boss but with the Russia investigation looming ever larger, the possibility of a Pence presidency following Trump’s resignation or even his impeachment should not be discounted.

Earlier this month, Paddy Power narrowed the odds on the president being ousted from 8/1 to 2/1 “in the wake of his dramatic U-turn, which saw him accept that Russia did meddle in the 2016 presidential election that he won”, reported Metro.

What do the polls say?

One of the latest surveys, from Politico/Morning Consult, carried out at the end of July, found that 35% of voters would re-elect Trump, while 48% would opt for an unamed Democratic candidate. The others said they did not know or held no opinion.

Given the option of Biden as the Democratic candidate, 37% would vote for Trump and 44% would vote for Biden.
